54
00:06:23,058 --> 00:06:25,101
- (Teddy) No!
- (gunshot)

55
00:06:26,770 --> 00:06:28,813
It’s just an anonymous room.

56
00:06:28,897 --> 00:06:31,441
There's nothing in the drawers.
But you look anyway.

57
00:06:31,524 --> 00:06:33,943
Nothing except the Gideon Bible,...

58
00:06:34,027 --> 00:06:37,906
...which l, of course, read religiously.
(laughs) Hm.

59
00:06:37,989 --> 00:06:41,993
You know who you are
and you know kind of all about yourself.

60
00:06:43,119 --> 00:06:47,957
But just for day-to-day stuff,
notes are really useful.

61
00:06:48,416 --> 00:06:53,046
Sammy Jankis had the same problem
but he really had no system.

62
00:06:53,129 --> 00:06:57,425
He wrote himself a ridiculous amount
of notes but he'd get them all mixed up.

63
00:06:57,509 --> 00:06:59,636
You really do need a system if...

64
00:06:59,719 --> 00:07:01,763
...if you’re gonna make it work.

65
00:07:52,814 --> 00:07:54,858
(presses bell)

66
00:07:56,693 --> 00:07:58,611
- Hi.
- Hi.

67
00:07:58,737 --> 00:08:01,948
- I'm Mr Shelby from 304.
- What can l do for you, Leonard?

68
00:08:02,031 --> 00:08:03,950
- Um...
- Burt.

69
00:08:04,033 --> 00:08:07,328
Burt. I'm not sure, l think
l may have asked you to hold my calls.

70
00:08:07,412 --> 00:08:10,290
- You don't know?
- I'm not too good on the phone.

71
00:08:10,373 --> 00:08:13,084
You said you like to look people in the eye
when you talk to them.

72
00:08:13,209 --> 00:08:14,544
Yeah, yeah.

73
00:08:14,627 --> 00:08:18,381
- You don't remember saying that.
- l have this condition.

74
00:08:18,548 --> 00:08:20,925
- A condition?
- It's my memory.

75
00:08:21,009 --> 00:08:23,553
- Amnesia?
- No, no, it's different from that.

76
00:08:23,636 --> 00:08:27,891
l have no short-term memory.
l know all about myself, l just...

77
00:08:27,974 --> 00:08:31,770
Since my injury l can't make
new memories. Everything fades.

78
00:08:31,853 --> 00:08:35,398
lf we talk for too long
I'll forget how we started...

79
00:08:35,523 --> 00:08:38,151
...and next time l see you
l won't remember this conversation.

80
00:08:38,234 --> 00:08:40,737
l don't even know if I've met you before.

81
00:08:41,029 --> 00:08:44,949
So if l seem a little strange
or rude, or something, uh...

82
00:08:45,909 --> 00:08:48,453
I've told you this before, haven't l?

83
00:08:48,536 --> 00:08:52,624
l don't mean to mess with you
but it's so weird.

84
00:08:52,707 --> 00:08:54,918
- You don't remember me at all?
- No.

85
00:08:55,043 --> 00:08:57,837
- We've talked a bunch of times.
- I'm sure we have.

86
00:08:58,922 --> 00:09:00,924
What's the last thing you remember?

87
00:09:01,174 --> 00:09:03,218
My wife.

88
00:09:03,593 --> 00:09:05,637
What's it like?

89
00:09:09,724 --> 00:09:11,768
It's like waking.

90
00:09:12,018 --> 00:09:14,229
It's like you just woke up.

91
00:09:14,896 --> 00:09:16,898
That must suck.

92
00:09:17,023 --> 00:09:18,566
It's all backwards.

93
00:09:18,650 --> 00:09:21,611
Like, maybe you got an idea
about what you want to do next...

94
00:09:21,694 --> 00:09:23,863
...but you don't remember
what you just did.

95
00:09:23,947 --> 00:09:26,616
l mean, I'm exactly the opposite...

96
00:09:26,658 --> 00:09:29,786
- How long have l been staying here?
- Couple of days.

97
00:09:29,869 --> 00:09:32,288
- And you're holding my calls?
- Like you said.

98
00:09:32,372 --> 00:09:34,791
OK, but this guy's an exception.

99
00:09:34,874 --> 00:09:36,292
You know this guy?

100
00:09:37,710 --> 00:09:41,548
- Yeah, it's your friend, right?
- What makes you think that?

101
00:09:41,631 --> 00:09:44,008
- l saw you together, that's all.
- He's not my friend.

102
00:09:44,092 --> 00:09:45,427
OK.

103
00:09:45,510 --> 00:09:49,305
lf he calls or shows up here,
give me a call in my room, OK?

104
00:09:49,389 --> 00:09:51,433
- What, his name's Teddy?
- Teddy, yeah.

105
00:09:51,516 --> 00:09:53,309
All right.

106
00:09:53,685 --> 00:09:56,646
Look, l hope my condition's
not gonna be a problem for you.

107
00:09:56,730 --> 00:09:59,023
Not as long as you remember
to pay the bill.

108
00:09:59,733 --> 00:10:01,776
Yeah. OK.

109
00:10:01,860 --> 00:10:03,153
Forty.

110
00:10:04,988 --> 00:10:06,406
This guy.

111
00:10:08,283 --> 00:10:09,492
He's here already.

112
00:10:11,453 --> 00:10:13,329
Lenny!

113
00:10:14,497 --> 00:10:18,626
You really need a system
if you’re gonna make it work.

114
00:10:18,710 --> 00:10:23,214
You kinda learn to trust your handwriting.
It becomes an important part of your life.

115
00:10:23,298 --> 00:10:27,260
You write yourself notes.
Where you put them is really important.

116
00:10:27,343 --> 00:10:30,055
You need a jacket that's got,
like, six pockets,...

117
00:10:30,138 --> 00:10:32,182
...particular pockets
for particular things.

118
00:10:32,307 --> 00:10:36,686
You just kinda learn to know where
things go and how the system works.

119
00:10:36,770 --> 00:10:39,147
You have to be wary of other people
writing stuff for you...

120
00:10:39,272 --> 00:10:42,358
...that is not going to make sense
or is gonna lead you astray.

121
00:10:42,442 --> 00:10:44,611
l don't know what makes people
take advantage...

122
00:10:44,694 --> 00:10:46,738
...of somebody with this condition.

123
00:10:46,821 --> 00:10:50,742
If you have a piece of information
which... is...

124
00:10:51,284 --> 00:10:55,413
...vital, writing on your body instead of
on a piece of paper can be the answer.

125
00:10:55,497 --> 00:10:57,540
It's a permanent way of keeping a note.

126
00:10:57,665 --> 00:10:59,709
(phone rings)

127
00:11:04,756 --> 00:11:06,591
Who is this?

128
00:11:14,140 --> 00:11:17,060
Remember Sammy Jankis.

129
00:11:28,947 --> 00:11:29,948
(door opens)

130
00:11:46,506 --> 00:11:48,800
- Sir, you left these at your table.
- Thanks.

131
00:11:49,843 --> 00:11:51,928
Ah, Lincoln Street?

132
00:11:52,011 --> 00:11:53,847
Just go straight out on Sixth Street,...

133
00:11:53,930 --> 00:11:56,099
- ...go east through town...
- I'm gonna write this down.

134
00:11:56,182 --> 00:11:59,519
- Oh, it's easy. Go straight out...
- Trust me, l need to write this down.

135
00:12:06,443 --> 00:12:08,486
The Discount Inn.

136
00:12:32,260 --> 00:12:34,304
Discount Inn.

137
00:12:35,138 --> 00:12:37,182
Natalie.

138
00:12:38,683 --> 00:12:40,560
My car.

139
00:12:42,228 --> 00:12:44,272
Teddy.

140
00:12:57,118 --> 00:12:59,162
John Edward Gammell.

141
00:13:00,997 --> 00:13:02,832
This guy told me his name was Teddy.

142
00:13:07,754 --> 00:13:09,714
Don't believe his lies.

143
00:13:16,388 --> 00:13:18,431
(dials)

144
00:13:20,183 --> 00:13:22,227
(ringing tone)

145
00:13:25,063 --> 00:13:27,107
- Yeah?
- Mr Gammell?

146
00:13:27,190 --> 00:13:29,234
- Lenny, is that you?
- John Gammell?

147
00:13:29,317 --> 00:13:31,694
Lenny, it's Teddy.
Stay there. I'll be right over.

148
00:13:31,736 --> 00:13:34,864
- OK. I'll be waiting.
- (line goes dead)

149
00:14:33,298 --> 00:14:35,341
White male.

150
00:14:36,426 --> 00:14:38,553
First name, John.

151
00:14:38,678 --> 00:14:42,515
Last name G for Gammell.

152
00:14:46,728 --> 00:14:48,563
Drugs.

153
00:14:48,646 --> 00:14:50,273
License plate.

154
00:14:51,483 --> 00:14:53,777
SG1 3...

155
00:14:56,196 --> 00:14:57,697
...7IU.

156
00:15:02,410 --> 00:15:04,412
It's him.

157
00:15:09,959 --> 00:15:12,587
I've found you, you fuck.

158
00:16:13,982 --> 00:16:16,401
You said we talked before.
l don't remember that.

159
00:16:16,484 --> 00:16:18,528
Yeah, but it's not amnesia.

160
00:16:18,611 --> 00:16:20,989
l remember up until my injury,
l just can't make new memories.

161
00:16:21,072 --> 00:16:23,366
So l can't remember talking to you.
What did we talk about?

162
00:16:23,450 --> 00:16:25,493
Oh, Sammy Jankis.

163
00:16:25,577 --> 00:16:28,204
l guess l tell people about Sammy
to help them understand.

164
00:16:28,288 --> 00:16:31,499
Sammy's story helps me understand
my own situation.

165
00:16:31,624 --> 00:16:34,294
Sammy wrote himself
endless amounts of notes.

166
00:16:34,377 --> 00:16:36,254
But he got mixed up.

167
00:16:36,963 --> 00:16:40,717
l have a more graceful solution
to the memory problem.

168
00:16:42,385 --> 00:16:44,429
I'm disciplined and organized.

169
00:16:44,512 --> 00:16:47,307
l use habit and routine
to make my life possible.

170
00:16:47,724 --> 00:16:49,768
Sammy had no drive,...

171
00:16:49,851 --> 00:16:51,895
...no reason to make it work.

172
00:16:52,395 --> 00:16:53,396
Me?

173
00:16:54,272 --> 00:16:55,940
Yeah,...

174
00:16:55,982 --> 00:16:58,068
...l got a reason.

175
00:17:09,788 --> 00:17:11,831
(activates alarm)

176
00:17:15,335 --> 00:17:18,421
Today, 1pm, meet Natalie for info.

177
00:17:19,589 --> 00:17:23,760
She has also lost someone.
She will help you out of pity.

178
00:17:40,902 --> 00:17:43,321
- Natalie.
- You don't remember me.

179
00:17:43,405 --> 00:17:46,157
- l should've explained. l have this cond...
- You did explain, Lenny.

180
00:17:46,908 --> 00:17:49,911
Please call me Leonard.
My wife called me Lenny.

181
00:17:49,994 --> 00:17:53,540
- l know, you told me.
- Then l probably told you l hated it.

182
00:17:53,623 --> 00:17:55,583
Yeah.

183
00:17:55,625 --> 00:17:58,545
Do you mind taking your glasses off?
It's hard for me to...

184
00:18:00,130 --> 00:18:00,922
Thanks.

185
00:18:01,005 --> 00:18:03,591
So, you have information for me?

186
00:18:03,675 --> 00:18:06,428
- Is that what your little note says?
- Yeah.

187
00:18:06,553 --> 00:18:09,973
Must be tough living your life
according to a couple of scraps of paper.

188
00:18:10,056 --> 00:18:13,476
Mix your laundry list with your grocery list
and you'll end up eating your underwear.

189
00:18:15,061 --> 00:18:17,355
l guess that's why you have
those freaky tattoos.

190
00:18:17,731 --> 00:18:20,024
Yeah, it's tough. It's almost impossible.

191
00:18:21,151 --> 00:18:24,654
Look, I'm sorry l don't remember you.
It's nothing personal.

192
00:18:27,615 --> 00:18:30,285
l do have information for you.

193
00:18:30,744 --> 00:18:32,954
You gave me a license-plate number.

194
00:18:33,788 --> 00:18:36,499
Had my friend at DMV trace it.

195
00:18:36,708 --> 00:18:38,418
Guess what name came up?

196
00:18:39,753 --> 00:18:43,006
John Edward Gammell. John G.

197
00:18:43,131 --> 00:18:44,382
Do you know him?

198
00:18:44,507 --> 00:18:48,178
No. But his face on his driver's license
looked really familiar.

199
00:18:48,303 --> 00:18:50,972
l think he's been in the bar, maybe.

200
00:18:51,056 --> 00:18:54,517
Here's a copy of his license,
his registration, photo and all.

201
00:18:54,601 --> 00:18:56,644
Are you sure you want this?

202
00:18:56,728 --> 00:18:59,397
- Have l told you what this man did?
- Yeah.

203
00:18:59,481 --> 00:19:01,858
Well, then you shouldn't have to ask.

204
00:19:01,941 --> 00:19:04,194
Even if you get revenge,
you're not gonna remember it.

205
00:19:04,277 --> 00:19:06,321
You're not even gonna know it happened.

206
00:19:06,404 --> 00:19:09,699
My wife deserves vengeance. It doesn't
make any difference if l know about it.

207
00:19:09,783 --> 00:19:12,118
Just because
there are things l don't remember...

208
00:19:12,202 --> 00:19:14,537
...doesn't make my actions meaningless.

209
00:19:14,662 --> 00:19:18,166
The world doesn't just disappear
when you close your eyes.

210
00:19:18,333 --> 00:19:21,961
Anyway, maybe I'll take a photograph
to remind myself.

211
00:19:22,045 --> 00:19:24,089
Get another freaky tattoo.

212
00:19:28,343 --> 00:19:30,595
Tell me about her again.

213
00:19:31,638 --> 00:19:33,014
Why?

214
00:19:33,139 --> 00:19:35,892
Because you like to remember her.

215
00:19:37,769 --> 00:19:39,813
She was beautiful.

216
00:19:41,314 --> 00:19:43,608
- To me she was perfect.
- No.

217
00:19:43,691 --> 00:19:46,528
Don't just recite the words.

218
00:19:47,529 --> 00:19:51,074
Close your eyes and remember her.

219
00:20:01,710 --> 00:20:03,753
You can just feel the details.

220
00:20:06,548 --> 00:20:09,801
The bits and pieces
you never bothered to put into words.

221
00:20:14,347 --> 00:20:17,434
And you can feel these extreme moments.

222
00:20:17,517 --> 00:20:19,310
Even if you don't want to.

223
00:20:21,938 --> 00:20:24,941
You put these together
and you get the feel of a person.

224
00:20:27,485 --> 00:20:29,446
Enough to know
how much you miss them.

225
00:20:35,577 --> 00:20:39,706
And how much you hate the person
who took them away.

226
00:20:48,840 --> 00:20:52,052
l, um, l added an address in here.

227
00:20:52,135 --> 00:20:55,555
It might be useful.
It's an abandoned place outside of town.

228
00:20:55,638 --> 00:20:58,558
Um, l guy l knew
used to do bigger deals there.

229
00:21:00,852 --> 00:21:02,687
It's isolated.

230
00:21:02,812 --> 00:21:04,814
Sounds perfect.

231
00:21:07,442 --> 00:21:10,612
- Do l owe you any...
- l wasn't helping you for money.

232
00:21:10,737 --> 00:21:12,906
- I'm sorry.
- It's OK.

233
00:21:12,989 --> 00:21:15,075
See, you have this condition.

234
00:21:17,118 --> 00:21:21,081
You still staying at the Discount Inn?
Room 304? Left it at my place.

235
00:21:26,252 --> 00:21:28,129
Yeah.

236
00:21:30,048 --> 00:21:32,801
- They treating you OK?
- l don't remember.

237
00:21:35,720 --> 00:21:37,764
You know what we have in common?

238
00:21:39,724 --> 00:21:42,143
We are both survivors.

239
00:21:45,522 --> 00:21:47,524
You take care, Leonard.

240
00:22:15,135 --> 00:22:17,429
Remember Sammy Jankis.

241
00:22:18,471 --> 00:22:22,600
l met Sammy through work. Insurance.
l was an investigator.

242
00:22:22,684 --> 00:22:25,186
I'd investigate the claims
to see which ones were phony.

243
00:22:25,270 --> 00:22:27,313
l had to see through people's bullshit.

244
00:22:27,397 --> 00:22:30,108
It was useful experience
cos now it's my life.

245
00:22:30,191 --> 00:22:33,486
When l meet someone,
l don't know if I've met them before.

246
00:22:33,570 --> 00:22:36,030
l have to look in their eyes
and try and figure them out.

247
00:22:36,156 --> 00:22:39,409
My job taught me the best way to find out
what someone knew was let them talk.

